\hypertarget{regex-functions}{%
\section{Regex Functions}\label{regex-functions}}

With the foundations of regex in hand, let's start using our learning to
create patterns of our own. To do so, we'll need to learn the Python
functions for actually applying regex to text.

Before we begin, we will introduce something called a \textbf{raw
string}. We will usually use raw strings of the form
\texttt{r"a\ raw\ string"} to construct a regex pattern, as opposed to
``standard'' strings of the form \texttt{"a\ non-raw\ string"}. The
reason why is fairly tedious, and not in scope for Data 100. Put simply,
a standard Python string interprets the character
\texttt{\textbackslash{}} in a different way to how it is used in regex.
Using raw strings avoids this issue.

\hypertarget{extraction-1}{%
\subsection{Extraction}\label{extraction-1}}

The \texttt{re} module of Python allows us to use regex on individual
strings. When working in \texttt{pandas}, \texttt{str} operations allow
us to apply vectorized regex functions to \texttt{Series} of strings.

To extract a regex match from a single string, we use the
\texttt{re.findall} function. \texttt{re.findall} will return a list
containing all matches of the regex pattern in a provided string.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ImportTok{import}\NormalTok{ re}
\NormalTok{text }\OperatorTok{=} \StringTok{"My social security number is 123{-}45{-}6789 bro, or actually maybe it’s 321{-}45{-}6789."}\OperatorTok{;}
\NormalTok{pattern }\OperatorTok{=} \VerbatimStringTok{r"[0{-}9]}\SpecialCharTok{\{3\}}\VerbatimStringTok{{-}[0{-}9]}\SpecialCharTok{\{2\}}\VerbatimStringTok{{-}[0{-}9]}\SpecialCharTok{\{4\}}\VerbatimStringTok{"}

\NormalTok{re.findall(pattern, text)  }
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
['123-45-6789', '321-45-6789']
\end{verbatim}

The \texttt{pandas} equivalent is \texttt{str.findall()}. The output of
\texttt{Series.str.findall()} is a new \texttt{Series} containing lists
of all matches contained in each string of the original \texttt{Series}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# Create a DataFrame of social security numbers to use as an example}
\NormalTok{df\_ssn }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame(}
\NormalTok{    [}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}987{-}65{-}4321\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}
     \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}forty\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}
     \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}123{-}45{-}6789 bro or 321{-}45{-}6789\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}
     \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}999{-}99{-}9999\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{],}
\NormalTok{    columns}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}SSN\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# An example Series of social security numbers}
\NormalTok{df\_ssn[}\StringTok{"SSN"}\NormalTok{]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
{} &                             SSN \\
\midrule
0 &                     987-65-4321 \\
1 &                           forty \\
2 &  123-45-6789 bro or 321-45-6789 \\
3 &                     999-99-9999 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# Using str.findall to extract SSNs}
\NormalTok{df\_ssn[}\StringTok{"SSN"}\NormalTok{].}\BuiltInTok{str}\NormalTok{.findall(pattern)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
{} &                         SSN \\
\midrule
0 &               [987-65-4321] \\
1 &                          [] \\
2 &  [123-45-6789, 321-45-6789] \\
3 &               [999-99-9999] \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}

\hypertarget{capturing-groups}{%
\subsubsection{Capturing groups}\label{capturing-groups}}

You might wonder: what if we only want to extract part of our full regex
pattern? For example, what if we only wanted to return the middle two
digits of each social security number?

Regex uses a piece of syntax called a \textbf{capturing group} to
specify what subset of a pattern should be ``captured''. Capturing
groups are denoted by parentheses \texttt{(\ )}. Earlier, we used
parentheses to outline the order of operations; depending on what regex
function we use, parentheses can sometimes also be interpreted as
capturing groups. \texttt{re.findall} and \texttt{str.findall} will both
interpret parentheses as capturing groups.

Consider the example text below. What if we wanted to extract the hour,
minute, and second mentioned in the message?

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{text }\OperatorTok{=} \StringTok{"I will meet you at 08:30:00 pm tomorrow"}      
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Capturing groups help us extract \emph{only} the information about the
time from this string. Notice that only the values enclosed in
parentheses in the regex pattern are returned.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{pattern }\OperatorTok{=} \StringTok{".*(\textbackslash{}d\textbackslash{}d):(\textbackslash{}d\textbackslash{}d):(\textbackslash{}d\textbackslash{}d).*"}
\NormalTok{matches }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ re.findall(pattern, text)}
\NormalTok{matches}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[('08', '30', '00')]
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{substitution}{%
\subsection{Substitution}\label{substitution}}

Another task we may encounter when working with text data is the need to
substitute portions of a string with a different character. For example,
we may want to replace messy HTML tags with an empty string to clean a
dataset.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# A messy string with extraneous HTML data}
\NormalTok{text }\OperatorTok{=} \StringTok{"\textless{}div\textgreater{}\textless{}td valign=\textquotesingle{}top\textquotesingle{}\textgreater{}Moo\textless{}/td\textgreater{}\textless{}/div\textgreater{}"}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

When working with individual strings, we use \texttt{re.sub}. The code
below seeks out HTML tags denoted with angle brackets
\texttt{\textless{}\ \textgreater{}} in the text and replaces them with
empty strings. The first argument to the function is the regex pattern,
the second is the string that should replace any matched text, and the
third is the test string on which to run the pattern.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{pattern }\OperatorTok{=} \VerbatimStringTok{r"\textless{}[\^{}\textgreater{}]+\textgreater{}"}
\NormalTok{re.sub(pattern, }\StringTok{""}\NormalTok{, text)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
'Moo'
\end{verbatim}

The vectorized \texttt{pandas} equivalent is \texttt{str.replace}. The
first argument to the function is the regex pattern we wish to use; the
second argument is the string that should replace the matched text. The
\texttt{regex} parameter tells \texttt{str.replace} to expect a regex
pattern.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# Create a DataFrame of HTML tags to use as an example}
\NormalTok{df\_html }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame([}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}\textless{}div\textgreater{}\textless{}td valign="top"\textgreater{}Moo\textless{}/td\textgreater{}\textless{}/div\textgreater{}\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}
                   \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}\textless{}a href="http://ds100.org"\textgreater{}Link\textless{}/a\textgreater{}\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}
                   \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}\textless{}b\textgreater{}Bold text\textless{}/b\textgreater{}\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{], columns}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}Html\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# An example Series of HTML data}
\NormalTok{df\_html[}\StringTok{"Html"}\NormalTok{]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
{} &                                  Html \\
\midrule
0 &  <div><td valign="top">Moo</td></div> \\
1 &   <a href="http://ds100.org">Link</a> \\
2 &                      <b>Bold text</b> \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df\_html[}\StringTok{"Html"}\NormalTok{].}\BuiltInTok{str}\NormalTok{.replace(pattern, }\StringTok{""}\NormalTok{, regex}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{True}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
{} &       Html \\
\midrule
0 &        Moo \\
1 &       Link \\
2 &  Bold text \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
